title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping
text: DivInsight package can used repurpose historical occurrence taxon data order generate diversity index values different dates locations.   Included package Colombia dataset, contains occurrence data taxon ‘Formicidae’ Family level 2000 2023. data queried Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF) database using rgbif package.   row occurrence dataframe data observed individual. dataset many variables important ones functions DivInsight pertain taxa names, coordinate location, dates observations.

what: Clusterise data from an entire province
title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping
text: Colombia dataset can subset province important function package clusterise_sites() can performed. function clusters data date generates centered coordinates cluster. result, data clusters represent sites various dates locations.     Furthermore, using optional argument group_radius, sites can grouped using specified radius metres.
code: Colombia_ValleCauca_dataframe <- subset(Colombia, stateProvince == "Valle del Cauca")   clusterised_ValleCauca_20kmGroups <- clusterise_sites(      dataframe = Colombia_ValleCauca_dataframe,   cluster_min_length = 30,   group_radius = 20000    )

what: Generate diversity statistics for each site
title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping
text: data ‘clusterised’ dataframe, row pertains site, can produced using generate_stats(). information includes dates observations, centred coordinates, diversity indices. indices included : Abundance (N), Species Richness (S), Shannon Diversity (H), Simpson Diversity (D), Inverse Simpson (Dinv), Margalef’s Diversity (d), Pielou’s Evenness (J).

title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping

code: plot_sites_trend_H(   clusterised_object = clusterised_ValleCauca_20kmGroups,   main_title = "Formicidae diversity in the Valle del Cauca province" )

title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping
text: charts show varying patterns diversity available time frames important know changes taking place. mapStart_siteCirc() can used create new map object site locations mapAdd_siteCirc() can used add sites.
code: ## create a new map using group 1's coordinates Colombia_ValleCauca_map <-       mapStart_siteCirc(          clusterised_object = ValleCauca_2,     site_name = "ValleCauca #2",     colour = "green"        )  ## add group 5's coordinates to the map object  Colombia_ValleCauca_map <-      mapAdd_siteCirc(          existing_map = Colombia_ValleCauca_map,          clusterised_object = ValleCauca_10,     site_name = "ValleCauca #10",     colour = "purple"        )  ## add group 6's coordinates to the map object Colombia_ValleCauca_map <-      mapAdd_siteCirc(          existing_map = Colombia_ValleCauca_map,          clusterised_object = ValleCauca_7,     site_name = "ValleCauca #7",     colour = "blue"        )  ## add group 8's coordinates to the map object Colombia_ValleCauca_map <-      mapAdd_siteCirc(          existing_map = Colombia_ValleCauca_map,          clusterised_object = ValleCauca_5,     site_name = "ValleCauca #5",     colour = "red"        )   ## view the map Colombia_ValleCauca_map

title: Species Composition Matrix Generation

title: Species Composition Matrix Generation

title: Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
text: DivInsight package can used repurpose historical occurrence taxon data order generate diversity statistics query environmental data different dates locations.   Included package ‘clusterised objects’ named Singapore_clst Malaysia_clst. objects contain clusters data taxon ‘Plantae’ Kingdom level Singapore Malaysia. data obtained querying data Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF) database using rgbif package organised data clusters using clusterise_sites() function. data cluster can considered site, instance, function set form clusters size least 30 observations radius 5000 metres.

title: Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
text: desired data queried RGBIF clusterised, next step query environmental data Storm Glass datagrid (www.stormglass.io). can done easily using query_climate_data() query_elevation_data() DivInsight. stats dataframe contains various abundance diversity statistics can generated using generate_stats().
code: ## generate and combine stats from both countries stats <- rbind(   generate_stats(Singapore_clst),   generate_stats(Malaysia_clst) )  ## store the API key (obtained by signing up to Storm Glass) API <- "9f8653c2-2efa-11ee-a654-0242ac130002-9f8654a8-2efa-11ee-a654-0242ac130002"  ## query climate data data_climate <- query_climate_data(stats_dataframe = stats, api_key = API)  ## query elevation data data_elev <- query_elevation_data(stats_dataframe = stats, api_key = API)

title: Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
text: queried, environmental data stored nested lists. best way access data, can analysed conveniently, collate stats dataframe using series loops.   Storm Glass query functions obtain climate data, available, hour. Considering row stats dataframe pertains one site single day, means 24 observations per site, best way store data calculate mean variable day/site. Users may edit based needs research
code: ## mean temperature (24hr) for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_temperature24hr[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$airTemperature$noaa)}) }  ## mean temperature (day time) for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_temperatureDay[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$airTemperature$noaa[7:19])}) }  ## mean precipitation for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_precipitation[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$precipitation$noaa)}) }  ## mean humidity for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_humidity[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$humidity$noaa)}) }  ## mean cloud cover for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_cloudCover[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$cloudCover$noaa)}) }  ## wind speed for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_windSpeed[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$windSpeed$noaa)}) }  ## elevation for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$elevation[i] <- data_elev[[i]]$data   stats$elevation <- as.numeric(stats$elevation)}) }

title: Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
text: wise check stats outliers mistakes. example, 50 lowest elevation values plotted using base R functions. negative values upon checking centred coordinates sites, can seen islands low elevation. however, single value approximately -20 metres.      Something gone wrong, base R functions can used investigate. can seen examining outlier row stats dataframe centred coordinates two decimal places. Additionally, upon checking raw data outlier cluster, obvious one unique pair coordinates entire data cluster. pair also two decimal places.   Furthermore, upon checking location centred coordinates site surprising see indicates location ocean, south Singapore, mainland Bukom Island. likely recording mistake resulted digits left second decimal place, leading incorrect location. Therefore, data removed.
code: plot(sort(stats$elevation) %>% head(50))   abline(h = -10, col = "darkviolet") ## find and store the row number that has an elevation value below -10 metres outlier_row_number <- which(stats$elevation < -10) outlier_row_number #> [1] 32   ## view the outlier row stats[outlier_row_number,] #>    longitude latitude site_group       date year month day   country stateProvince kingdom       phylum         class   N   S        H         D     Dinv        d         J day_length mean_temperature24hr mean_temperatureDay mean_precipitation mean_humidity mean_cloudCover mean_windSpeed elevation #> 38    103.75     1.25         56 2009-07-13 2009     7  13 Singapore          <NA> Plantae Tracheophyta Magnoliopsida 483 300 5.602887 0.9959321 245.8261 48.38175 0.9823108   12.18704                   NA                  NA                 NA            NA              NA             NA -20.37201   ## view the unique coordinate values of the outlier cluster Singapore_clst[[1]][[outlier_row_number]]$decimalLatitude %>% unique #> [1] 1.25 Singapore_clst[[1]][[outlier_row_number]]$decimalLongitude %>% unique #> [1] 103.75   ## remove the outlier row from the stats dataframe stats <- stats[-outlier_row_number,]

title: Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
text: point script, environmental variable data diversity statistics compiled one dataframe ready analysed. , linear regression used model relationship wind speed variable Pielou’s evenness index.   Storm Glass datagrid complete climate data times locations likely NAs queried climate data. Therefore, NA values removed using complete.cases() function base R.      statistically significant positive relationship wind speed Pielou’s evenness (J). suggests wind speed increases evenness plant species Singapore Peninsular Malaysia also increases.   Many ecological inferences can made finding obvious one may higher wind speeds cause balanced distribution plant seeds.
code: ## check for NA values NA %in% stats$mean_windSpeed #> [1] TRUE   ## filter out NAs  stats_windspeed_Complete <- stats[complete.cases(stats["mean_windSpeed"]),]   ## build a linear model and view the output lm1 <- lm(J ~ mean_windSpeed, data = stats_windspeed_Complete)  summary(lm1) #>  #> Call: #> lm(formula = J ~ mean_windSpeed, data = stats_windspeed_Complete) #>  #> Residuals: #>       Min        1Q    Median        3Q       Max  #> -0.212339 -0.012620  0.008052  0.025877  0.059791  #>  #> Coefficients: #>                Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)     #> (Intercept)    0.926815   0.010613  87.326   <2e-16 *** #> mean_windSpeed 0.010277   0.004193   2.451   0.0164 *   #> --- #> Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1 #>  #> Residual standard error: 0.0451 on 83 degrees of freedom #> Multiple R-squared:  0.06748,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.05625  #> F-statistic: 6.007 on 1 and 83 DF,  p-value: 0.01635   ## plot the linear model ggplot(data = stats_windspeed_Complete, aes(x = mean_windSpeed, y = J)) +      geom_point() +      geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "darkviolet") +      labs(x = "mean wind speed  (m/s)", y = "Pielou's evenness (J)") +      ggtitle("Linear Regression: Wind Speed vs. Species Evenness (y = 0.01x + 0.927 | R2 = 0.068, P = 0.016)")  #> `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

title: Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
text: , linear regression used model relationship elevation variable Pielou’s evenness index.      statistically significant negative relationship elevation Pielou’s evenness (J). suggests higher elevations evenness plant species decreased Singapore Peninsular Malaysia.   inference finding harsher environmental factors lead specialisation /competition meaning certain species likely dominate habitats higher elevations.
code: ## check for NA values NA %in% stats$elevation #> [1] FALSE   ## build a linear model lm2 <- lm(J ~ elevation, data = stats)  summary(lm2) #>  #> Call: #> lm(formula = J ~ elevation, data = stats) #>  #> Residuals: #>       Min        1Q    Median        3Q       Max  #> -0.237666 -0.015819  0.007943  0.035954  0.088443  #>  #> Coefficients: #>               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)     #> (Intercept)  9.522e-01  6.209e-03   153.4  < 2e-16 *** #> elevation   -8.961e-05  2.800e-05    -3.2  0.00187 **  #> --- #> Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1 #>  #> Residual standard error: 0.05449 on 94 degrees of freedom #> Multiple R-squared:  0.09825,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.08866  #> F-statistic: 10.24 on 1 and 94 DF,  p-value: 0.001873   ## create a scatter plot  ggplot(data = stats, aes(x = elevation, y = J)) +      geom_point() +      geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "darkviolet") +      labs(x = "elevation (m)", y = "Pielou's evenness (J)") +      ggtitle("Linear Regression: Elevation vs. Species Evenness (y = -0.0000861x + 0.952 | R2 = 0.098, P = 0.002)")  #> `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

text: DivInsight package can used repurpose historical occurrence taxon data order generate diversity statistics query environmental data different dates locations.   Included package ‘clusterised objects’ named Singapore_clst Malaysia_clst. objects contain clusters data taxon ‘Plantae’ Kingdom level Singapore Malaysia. data obtained querying data Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF) database using rgbif package organised data clusters using clusterise_sites() function. data cluster can considered site, instance, function set form clusters size least 30 observations radius 5000 metres.

title: Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
text: desired data queried RGBIF clusterised, next step query environmental data Storm Glass datagrid (www.stormglass.io). can done easily using query_climate_data() query_elevation_data() DivInsight. stats dataframe contains various abundance diversity statistics can generated using generate_stats().
code: ## generate and combine stats from both countries stats <- rbind(   generate_stats(Singapore_clst),   generate_stats(Malaysia_clst) )  ## store the API key (obtained by signing up to Storm Glass) API <- "9f8653c2-2efa-11ee-a654-0242ac130002-9f8654a8-2efa-11ee-a654-0242ac130002"  ## query climate data data_climate <- query_climate_data(stats_dataframe = stats, api_key = API)  ## query elevation data data_elev <- query_elevation_data(stats_dataframe = stats, api_key = API)

title: Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
text: queried, environmental data stored nested lists. best way access data, can analysed conveniently, collate stats dataframe using series loops.   Storm Glass query functions obtain climate data, available, hour. Considering row stats dataframe pertains one site single day, means 24 observations per site, best way store data calculate mean variable day/site. Users may edit based needs research
code: ## mean temperature (24hr) for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_temperature24hr[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$airTemperature$noaa)}) }  ## mean temperature (day time) for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_temperatureDay[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$airTemperature$noaa[7:19])}) }  ## mean precipitation for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_precipitation[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$precipitation$noaa)}) }  ## mean humidity for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_humidity[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$humidity$noaa)}) }  ## mean cloud cover for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_cloudCover[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$cloudCover$noaa)}) }  ## wind speed for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$mean_windSpeed[i] <- mean(data_climate[[i]]$hours$windSpeed$noaa)}) }  ## elevation for(i in 1:length(stats[,1])){   suppressWarnings({stats$elevation[i] <- data_elev[[i]]$data   stats$elevation <- as.numeric(stats$elevation)}) }

title: Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
text: wise check stats outliers mistakes. example, 50 lowest elevation values plotted using base R functions. negative values upon checking centred coordinates sites, can seen islands low elevation. however, single value approximately -20 metres.      Something gone wrong, base R functions can used investigate. can seen examining outlier row stats dataframe centred coordinates two decimal places. Additionally, upon checking raw data outlier cluster, obvious one unique pair coordinates entire data cluster. pair also two decimal places.   Furthermore, upon checking location centred coordinates site surprising see indicates location ocean, south Singapore, mainland Bukom Island. likely recording mistake resulted digits left second decimal place, leading incorrect location. Therefore, data removed.
code: plot(sort(stats$elevation) %>% head(50))   abline(h = -10, col = "darkviolet") ## find and store the row number that has an elevation value below -10 metres outlier_row_number <- which(stats$elevation < -10) outlier_row_number #> [1] 32   ## view the outlier row stats[outlier_row_number,] #>    longitude latitude site_group       date year month day   country stateProvince kingdom       phylum         class   N   S        H         D     Dinv        d         J day_length mean_temperature24hr mean_temperatureDay mean_precipitation mean_humidity mean_cloudCover mean_windSpeed elevation #> 38    103.75     1.25         56 2009-07-13 2009     7  13 Singapore          <NA> Plantae Tracheophyta Magnoliopsida 483 300 5.602887 0.9959321 245.8261 48.38175 0.9823108   12.18704                   NA                  NA                 NA            NA              NA             NA -20.37201   ## view the unique coordinate values of the outlier cluster Singapore_clst[[1]][[outlier_row_number]]$decimalLatitude %>% unique #> [1] 1.25 Singapore_clst[[1]][[outlier_row_number]]$decimalLongitude %>% unique #> [1] 103.75   ## remove the outlier row from the stats dataframe stats <- stats[-outlier_row_number,]

title: Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
text: point script, environmental variable data diversity statistics compiled one dataframe ready analysed. , linear regression used model relationship wind speed variable Pielou’s evenness index.   Storm Glass datagrid complete climate data times locations likely NAs queried climate data. Therefore, NA values removed using complete.cases() function base R.      statistically significant positive relationship wind speed Pielou’s evenness (J). suggests wind speed increases evenness plant species Singapore Peninsular Malaysia also increases.   Many ecological inferences can made finding obvious one may higher wind speeds cause balanced distribution plant seeds.
code: ## check for NA values NA %in% stats$mean_windSpeed #> [1] TRUE   ## filter out NAs  stats_windspeed_Complete <- stats[complete.cases(stats["mean_windSpeed"]),]   ## build a linear model and view the output lm1 <- lm(J ~ mean_windSpeed, data = stats_windspeed_Complete)  summary(lm1) #>  #> Call: #> lm(formula = J ~ mean_windSpeed, data = stats_windspeed_Complete) #>  #> Residuals: #>       Min        1Q    Median        3Q       Max  #> -0.212339 -0.012620  0.008052  0.025877  0.059791  #>  #> Coefficients: #>                Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)     #> (Intercept)    0.926815   0.010613  87.326   <2e-16 *** #> mean_windSpeed 0.010277   0.004193   2.451   0.0164 *   #> --- #> Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1 #>  #> Residual standard error: 0.0451 on 83 degrees of freedom #> Multiple R-squared:  0.06748,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.05625  #> F-statistic: 6.007 on 1 and 83 DF,  p-value: 0.01635   ## plot the linear model ggplot(data = stats_windspeed_Complete, aes(x = mean_windSpeed, y = J)) +      geom_point() +      geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, colour = "darkviolet") +      labs(x = "mean wind speed  (m/s)", y = "Pielou's evenness (J)") +      ggtitle("Linear Regression: Wind Speed vs. Species Evenness (y = 0.01x + 0.927 | R2 = 0.068, P = 0.016)")  #> `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

title: Analyzing Diversity-Environment Relationships
text: , linear regression used model relationship elevation variable Pielou’s evenness index.      statistically significant negative relationship elevation Pielou’s evenness (J). suggests higher elevations evenness plant species decreased Singapore Peninsular Malaysia.   inference finding harsher environmental factors lead specialisation /competition meaning certain species likely dominate habitats higher elevations.

title: Determining Taxon Range
text: function mapStart_rangePoly() can used plot polygon interactive map using convex hull coordinates. create shape using outer coordinates dataset. mapAdd_rangePoly() can used add polygon shapes onto existing map using different set coordinates.   example, frog, salamander, caecilian occurrence coordinates years available (2011-2022) Andes dataset plotted show range taxa. can seen plot frog species observed throughout entire Andes salamanders caecilians observed northern Andes.
code: ## split the occurrence dataframe into the order classes orders <- split(Andes, Andes$order)    ## start the map with all frog occurences map <- mapStart_rangePoly(   taxon_dataframe = orders$Anura,   site_name =  "Frogs",   colour = "darkgreen",   poly_opacity = 0.4 )  ## add salamander occurrences map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(   existing_map = map,   taxon_dataframe =  orders$Caudata,   site_name =  "Salamanders",   colour = "darkorange",   poly_opacity = 0.4 )  ## add caecilian occurrences map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(   existing_map = map,   taxon_dataframe =  orders$Gymnophiona,   site_name =  "Caecilians",   colour = "darkviolet",   poly_opacity = 0.4 )  ## display the map map

what: Calculate taxon range of three frog species
title: Determining Taxon Range
text: range metres selected taxon can calculated using functions available package. , subset occurrence data three species, subsequently split subsets individual years. use base R functions apply find_taxon_range() year species.
code: ## subset the chosen species species1 <- subset(Andes, species == "Pristimantis achatinus")   species2 <- subset(Andes, species == "Leptodactylus fragilis")  species3 <- subset(Andes, species == "Epipedobates anthonyi")     ## split the species datsets by year into new objects species1_years <- split(species1, species1$year) species2_years <- split(species2, species2$year) species3_years <- split(species3, species3$year)    ## find the taxon range for each year of the first species and store into a datframe taxon_range_list_sp1 <- lapply(species1_years, find_taxon_range) taxon_range_df_sp1 <- data.frame(   Year = names(taxon_range_list_sp1),   Range_metres = as.numeric(taxon_range_list_sp1) ) taxon_range_df_sp1 #>    Year Range_metres #> 1  2011     990169.4 #> 2  2012     851767.3 #> 3  2013    1142328.2 #> 4  2014    1106831.7 #> 5  2015    1228173.2 #> 6  2016    1075690.4 #> 7  2017    1268015.2 #> 8  2018    1254402.9 #> 9  2019    1268224.9 #> 10 2020    1035614.8 #> 11 2021    1210442.9 #> 12 2022    1303926.5    ## title: Determining Taxon Range
code: ## create a map with a range polygon using the species' entire dataset then add polygons for separate years  map <- mapStart_rangePoly(species1, "Pristimantis achatinus", site_legend = F, poly_opacity = 0.4)  map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(map, species1_years[[2]], "2012", "darkred") map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(map, species1_years[[6]], "2016", "darkblue") map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(map, species1_years[[10]], "2020", "darkgreen")    ## add the polygons for the second frog species map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(map, species2, "Leptodactylus fragilis", "black", site_legend = F)  map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(map, species2_years[[2]], "2012", "darkred", site_legend = F) map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(map, species2_years[[6]], "2016", "darkblue", site_legend = F) map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(map, species2_years[[10]], "2020", "darkgreen", site_legend = F)    ## add polygons for the third frog species map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(map, species3, "Epipedobates anthonyi", "black", site_legend = F)  map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(map, species3_years[[2]], "2012", "darkred", site_legend = F) map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(map, species3_years[[6]], "2016", "darkblue", site_legend = F) map <- mapAdd_rangePoly(map, species3_years[[10]], "2020", "darkgreen", site_legend = F)    ## display the map map

title: Species Composition Matrix Generation

title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping
text: DivInsight package can used repurpose historical occurrence taxon data order generate diversity index values different dates locations.   Included package Colombia dataset, contains occurrence data taxon ‘Formicidae’ Family level 2000 2023. data queried Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF) database using rgbif package.   row occurrence dataframe data observed individual. dataset many variables important ones functions DivInsight pertain taxa names, coordinate location, dates observations.

what: Clusterise data from an entire province
title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping
text: Colombia dataset can subset province important function package clusterise_sites() can performed. function clusters data date generates centered coordinates cluster. result, data clusters represent sites various dates locations.     Furthermore, using optional argument group_radius, sites can grouped using specified radius metres.
code: Colombia_ValleCauca_dataframe <- subset(Colombia, stateProvince == "Valle del Cauca")   clusterised_ValleCauca_20kmGroups <- clusterise_sites(      dataframe = Colombia_ValleCauca_dataframe,   cluster_min_length = 30,   group_radius = 20000    )

what: Generate diversity statistics for each site
title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping
text: data ‘clusterised’ dataframe, row pertains site, can produced using generate_stats(). information includes dates observations, centred coordinates, diversity indices. indices included : Species Richness (S), Shannon Diversity (H), Simpson Diversity (D), Inverse Simpson (Dinv), Margalef’s Diversity (d), Pielou’s Evenness (J).

title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping
text: Package functions can used easily plot diversity values time.
code: plot_sites_trend_H(   clusterised_object = clusterised_ValleCauca_20kmGroups,   main_title = "Formicidae diversity in the Valle del Cauca province" )

title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping
text: clusterised object contains two elements. first element contains clustered data second contains metadata. metadata centred coordinates dates site well group label.   group_radius argument used clusterise_sites() function label assigned group. using [[2]] index, metadata can viewed. column labeled site_group displays group labels.     Also, base R commands can used quickly see many sites group help us decide groups examine .

title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping
text: , groups 2, 10, 7, 5 examined using filter_groups_by_number() store group’s data plot using plot_sites_scatter_H().
code: ValleCauca_2 <- filter_groups_by_number(clusterised_ValleCauca_20kmGroups, 2) ValleCauca_10 <- filter_groups_by_number(clusterised_ValleCauca_20kmGroups, 10) ValleCauca_7 <- filter_groups_by_number(clusterised_ValleCauca_20kmGroups, 7) ValleCauca_5 <- filter_groups_by_number(clusterised_ValleCauca_20kmGroups, 5)  grid.arrange(   plot_sites_scatter_H(ValleCauca_2,  main = "Shannon's H at ValleCauca #2"),    plot_sites_scatter_H(ValleCauca_10, main = "Shannon's H at ValleCauca #10"),   ncol = 2 ) #> Warning: Use of `stats_dataframe$date` is discouraged. #> ℹ Use `date` instead. #> Warning: Use of `stats_dataframe$H` is discouraged. #> ℹ Use `H` instead.  grid.arrange(   plot_sites_scatter_H(ValleCauca_7, main = "Shannon's H at ValleCauca #7"),   plot_sites_scatter_H(ValleCauca_5, main = "Shannon's H at ValleCauca #5"),   ncol = 2 )

code: # create a new map using group 1's coordinates Colombia_ValleCauca_map <-       map_start(          clusterised_object = ValleCauca_2,     site_name = "ValleCauca #2",     colour = "green"        )  # add group 5's coordinates to the map object  Colombia_ValleCauca_map <-      map_add(          existing_map = Colombia_ValleCauca_map,          clusterised_object = ValleCauca_10,     site_name = "ValleCauca #10",     colour = "purple"        )  # add group 6's coordinates to the map object Colombia_ValleCauca_map <-      map_add(          existing_map = Colombia_ValleCauca_map,          clusterised_object = ValleCauca_7,     site_name = "ValleCauca #7",     colour = "blue"        )  # add group 8's coordinates to the map object Colombia_ValleCauca_map <-      map_add(          existing_map = Colombia_ValleCauca_map,          clusterised_object = ValleCauca_5,     site_name = "ValleCauca #5",     colour = "red"        )   # view the map Colombia_ValleCauca_map

title: Diversity Statistics: Auto Clustering, Charting, and Mapping
text: subset data exact location pair longitude/latitude coordinates can used subset_by_coordinate_ref(). coordinate_reference argument mark centre location distance_threshold mark radius location metres.   function used argument value clusterise_sites() function get clusterised data two locations Colombia. radius location set 25km.
code: # clusterise coordinate reference location 1 clusterised_Colombia_CoordRef_1 <- clusterise_sites(      dataframe =          subset_by_coordinate_ref(       dataframe = Colombia,       coordinate_reference = c(-73.325377, 3.956982),       distance_threshold = 25000),      cluster_min_length = 30     )   # clusterise coordinate reference location 2 clusterised_Colombia_CoordRef_2 <- clusterise_sites(      dataframe =           subset_by_coordinate_ref(       dataframe = Colombia,       coordinate_reference = c(-71.889919, 4.470524),       distance_threshold = 25000),      cluster_min_length = 30     )   # view meta data for location 1 print(clusterised_Colombia_CoordRef_1[[2]]) #>    longitude latitude site_group       date #> 1  -73.46702 4.058576          1 2000-10-01 #> 2  -73.46702 4.058576          1 2000-10-06 #> 3  -73.47267 4.073333          1 2015-10-13 #> 4  -73.47267 4.073333          1 2015-11-19 #> 5  -73.47267 4.073333          1 2016-02-15 #> 6  -73.47267 4.073333          1 2016-02-24 #> 7  -73.47267 4.073333          1 2016-05-24 #> 8  -73.47267 4.073333          1 2016-06-13 #> 9  -73.47267 4.073333          1 2016-08-03 #> 10 -73.36824 4.083131          1 2022-11-09 #> 11 -73.38409 4.080567          1 2022-11-11 #> 12 -73.37865 4.091503          1 2022-11-14  # view meta data for location 2 print(clusterised_Colombia_CoordRef_2[[2]]) #>   longitude latitude site_group       date #> 1 -71.73596 4.340693          1 2012-05-01 #> 2 -71.81433 4.530222          1 2015-09-16 #> 3 -71.81433 4.530222          1 2015-10-13 #> 4 -71.81433 4.530222          1 2015-11-19 #> 5 -71.81433 4.530222          1 2016-02-15

title: Diversity Index Calculation & Visualisation for Taxa and Location
text: DivInsight currently uses functions compatiable datasets queried Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF) regards occurrence data, well Storm Glass datagrid (www.stormglass.io) regards environmental data. future, data sources explored order potentially improve validity results provided package. Given laborious process querying large datasets GBIF using R, vignette tutorial provided show users efficient way . especially helpful users unfamiliar rgbif package. Various utility functions added make scripts efficient.
